Today we are going back to basics and we are talking about heart rate zones- what they are, how to your find your zones, why each zone matters, and what training looks like and feels like in each zone.  Whether you are a seasoned athlete, or just coming into structured training, this podcast will help you learn or re-learn about heart rate training. 
Heart rate zones let you know how hard your heart is working and what energy source you’re using — carbohydrates or fat.  Your body is different every day; and by training where you are at, and not where you think you should be, you will make the most fitness gains and increase performance. Also, listen closely for Angela’s interesting way to describe the RPE scale for a zero and a ten, which involves a bear.  She might be on to something.  Have a listen!

If you want to live, constantly die. Yup, If you heard one of our podcasts on me talking about DEATH, it becomes even more appropriate here. (Check out the IRACELIKEAGIRL podcast if you haven’t already. I mean, where have you been?! We’re killing it!). 

I was riding today, and as always, listening to a variety of things from podcasts, to interviews, to heavy metal and rap (I love Enimen btw). 
They can’t kill you if you’re already dead is to me, “I live like I’m already dead.” The idea?! - surrendering completely to the moment, whatever it brings, with no past fear lurking in the shadows or skeletons in our closet desperately trying to scare us. 

No one can harm you if you’re already dead. And this is what I want to hone in on. We have all been thru adversity in life, some maybe more than others, but we have all had adversity and if you embrace this, you can be unbreakable. 

As I was riding today, this quote just hit me. As athletes, as humans, we need to embrace life and where we are as it is. We are a cycle of death and rebirth. Anything from relationships changing to injuries, to anything where life feels it’s falling apart - it’s a DEATH of the OLD you. And a moment of opportunity to start NEW.  It’s about not only seeing the silver linings, but wanting the destruction and moments of death to happen ALOT. We learn this way, we become better human beings. We learn and love more about WHO we are. And above all, we don’t give a F%*()$ about what we ASSUME people think or say of us, if we’re enough, if we are loved - because it’s all just stories - words we decide in our heads that provide judgment. 

Overtime we develop a persona of ourselves. But with the idea, that we are already dead, our own persona can’t kill us and hold us trapped in a box of self-judgement, fear and worry. 

I’m learning to embrace the uncertainty of life and that, that is freeing. DIE. Kill our egos. And let’s just see what we’ve got. 

Also inspired by many words from @petercron.e - ❤️

WHAT IS IRACELIKEAGIRL? 

#IWD International Women’s Day - For me, it’s all about stomping out the stigma associated with the word “girl”. $^%# society thinking it’s a weak term for Woman.  Teams @iracelikeagirl and @girlsgetgritty (Triathlon and Off-road women teams) are made of some of the most badass, if not THE TOP badass women I know. 

I founded these teams to support, inspire and help others bring out their inner selves that have been hidden because of society, thought process and the “not good enough” ideas we get taught from our experiences of growing up as a girl.  These teams are for all female oriented persons. And,  I’m pretty damn proud of what and who this team is made of! … 

To me, the idea that being called a “girl” is a negative term, is an unfortunate  society drive $^%& mindset. I know that not all women feel this way, that perhaps one feels when they are referred to being a girl, it’s an attempt to deny a woman of her power, grace, maturity, and strength. IRACELIKEAGIRL and GIRLSGETGRITTY is about just the opposite – it’s about celebrating what it means to be feminine. As a team, we are emboldened with the same fierceness women embrace during a night out with the “girls”. This is the strength behind the girl. We are a community of women/ladies/gals that use ‘girl’ to support all ages and all abilities in sport – all with a bit of splash of feminine sass!    WE are about redefining what it means to be “like a girl.” We achieve this by showing up and giving it our best… every race, every day.  Turn toward the word with STRENGTH and POWER - reclaim it:  a person who is fun, adventurous, exploratory and bold; a woman to me is strong, confident, responsible, nurturing and global in her thinking. Probably the most important piece to all of this is, is the integration of girl WITH woman power in each woman herself, allowing that fun and damn grit and grace shine. 

@girlsgetgritty @iracelikeagirl - keep rocking this world 🌎!

• It is estimated that approximately 30% of all new women cancer diagnoses will be breast cancer this year. 
• There are over 3.8 million breast cancer survivors in the United States.

My coach asked me the following: “Self-Doubt
Take two minutes, and give me your perspective…
Is self-doubt a good thing? A bad thing? Both? Neither?
Why?” I thought I’d share - my let’s see what I’ve got mentality. 

As an athlete, the question of whether self-doubt is good, bad, or neither has been an ongoing debate. Through my experiences, I recognize that self-doubt has both advantages and disadvantages.

On one hand, self-doubt can limit personal growth and progress if it becomes pervasive and interferes with our goals. When we fixate on past failures or future uncertainties, it can be paralyzing and turn into an expectation to fail. It can lead to negative self-talk and undermine our self-confidence, affecting how we perform both in training and competitions.

On the other hand, I have found that self-doubt can be used positively as a tool for motivation and self-improvement. When I doubt my ability to complete a difficult training session or competition, I try to reframe it quickly into a “Let’s see what I’ve got” mentality. Shifting my mindset towards a more confident and focused state in the moment has been a powerful way to turn self-doubt into excitement, allowing me to perform at my best.

Furthermore, I believe that self-doubt and anxiety share similarities in that they can both come with a positive or negative connotation depending on how we approach them. Similar to how anxiety can be seen as either being scared or excited, self-doubt can be seen the same way. If we view self-doubt as an opportunity for growth and put ourselves in the present moment without allowing negative judgment to dictate us, it can be used positively to fuel our performance.

I believe that self-doubt can be a powerful tool for growth and achievement as long as we learn to manage it in a healthy way. By practicing reframing it positively into an opportunity for growth and focusing on the present moment, we can use self-doubt to build resilience and improve performance. #letsseewhativegot mentality.

These graphs show how my menstrual cycle affects my cycling performance. Think of it like riding a rollercoaster, but instead of ups and downs, it's power output (pink line) and heart rate (red line) performance! (These were 2 group rides on consecutive days I got my period the evening of the first ride). 

Premenstrual and always the day before, I feel like a slug on the bike. My power output is weak and ability to sustain my aerobic heart rate and power is a struggle.

But after - literally the day I get my period, I am stronger and my ability to work hard is significantly better (even with cramps). I can generate sustained power and heart rate like a champ.

I share this because it IS a thing. And it’s real, and normal. I haven’t experienced a way to really showcase this on two consecutive days for two long days (group rides), so it’s awesome to finally be able to see this in graph form and similar rides! I didn’t even know I was going to get it. 

Here’s some info to remind us all on the reason this happens (I have raced premenstrual and it is more difficult. I just suck it up and accept what is, and do my best!)

During the menstrual cycle, there are fluctuations in hormone levels that can affect a woman's physical and mental state. In the first two weeks of the menstrual cycle, estrogen levels rise, leading up to ovulation. Estrogen is known to have a positive effect on endurance performance, as it enhances the use of carbohydrates for energy and improves oxygen uptake by the muscles.

However, in the second half of the menstrual cycle, after ovulation, progesterone levels rise, which can have a negative effect on athletic performance. Progesterone is known to cause water retention and bloating, which can make women feel heavy and sluggish. It can also cause fatigue, as it has a sedative effect on the body.

Once menstruation begins, estrogen and progesterone levels drop, and many women report feeling stronger and more energetic. The drop in hormone levels can also lead to an increase in endorphins, which can improve mood and provide a natural boost of energy.

I had a wonderful conversation with my coach, who is also a very close friend. During our talk, he helped me articulate my self-concept and mindset, which has left me feeling ready to tackle whatever tomorrow brings. Here’s to that conversation: 

Lately, there has been a lot of emphasis on the importance of being aggressive, and how it's necessary to show this trait in order to succeed. However, in my experience, aggression is often fueled by ego and anger, which can hinder my ability to achieve a state of flow. When it comes to racing, I find that a quiet fierceness and an open mind are what enable me to perform at my best. It's in this space that the true essence of racing can thrive.

I believe that aggression doesn't have to be loud or forceful. Instead, it can manifest itself in a quiet fierceness that is rooted in determination and focus. This kind of aggression is less about dominating others and more about pushing oneself to the limit, no matter what obstacles may arise.

In the context of racing, this means having the discipline and mental fortitude to stay focused on the task at hand, even when the competition is fierce or the conditions are challenging. It means channeling one's energy into a controlled, calculated effort that maximizes performance and minimizes risk.

Ultimately, I believe that the most successful racers are those who are able to find this balance between aggression and control, between pushing hard and staying calm. It's a delicate dance, but one that is essential for achieving (your) greatness in a race. 

This is my third @unboundgravel dance. Here’s to a great day of racing and the joy of discovering what lies ahead!

The 4 miles of peanut butter mud at mile 11 had us all feeling like we were stuck in quicksand - hiking and cleaning muck off our wheels every 100 yards. And once we hit dry gravel, the heat started to rise, soaring into the high 80s. In hindsight, I focused too much on fuelling with my USWE (@thefeedme!), and after the mud section, I found myself craving/NEEDING water.

The first aid station came after 80  miles, but I was already struggling with energy levels. I lost my legs for a bit and hit a low point, but once we reached the OASIS at 124 (water station), it was like a second wind. I drank 4 full bottles of water and reloaded my hydration pack, and from there, I felt like I had new life breathed into me.

But then the storm hit. The rain and sleet may have surprised us all, but I knew I had to keep my heart rate up to avoid becoming a DNF. In full-on race-survival-mode, I pushed myself as hard as I could and forced the small crew I was with to follow suit. The sideways rain, mud, and muck made it an intense and unforgettable experience. I shocked myself by how well I rode through that section. Funny how the thought of survival mode can kick your own butt into gear, right?

Despite all these obstacles, I'm extremely proud of how I persevered and fought through it. Overheating, dehydration, shivering, needing a rain jacket at the 2nd aid station - it was tough. But to have completed such a demanding race is a true testament to what we are all capable of when we put our minds to it.

Thank you to @shimanogravel S neutral support, the OOFOS crew team for being rockstars and supporting me through my aid stations, and my amazing partners who made this unforgettable experience possible. And to my fellow racers, thank you for pushing me to constantly improve and strive to be better. I couldn't have done it without you all. Here's to the next adventure - off to @fnldgrvl!

Today was a total disaster, haha! Around mile 60 on the bike, everything just went downhill. I felt nauseous, foggy-headed, and downright awful. I was tempted to call it quits, but you know what they say, things can turn around unexpectedly. So, I kept pushing forward, hoping for just that. 

When I reached T2, things only got worse. I changed into my running shoes and started to run, but after roughly 10 minutes, I had a serious internal debate with myself. Should I stop? Should I keep going? I stopped. I walked. And then, in a moment of crazy determination, I turned back towards the course and tried again. Can you believe it? I did this not once, not twice, but three times! I think I "ran" the same 100 yards over and over before I finally broke down in tears and accepted my fate.

My head was pounding, and I felt dizzy and just terribly “off”. It was like being on a wild, trippy rollercoaster ride. 

The medical team took care of me for a whopping two hours. They even had the pleasure of testing my temperature in the most delightful way, four times! Low rectal temperatures and non-stop nausea, swelling, head pain - hypernatremia most likely the culprit or a virus. 

Yes, it was quite ambitious to tackle an Ironman after Leadville. I'm well aware of that. However, I wanted to give it a shot. 

So there I was, in the midst of the race, battling with my own emotions. Tears welled up in my eyes as I grappled with a mix of frustration, sadness, and the realization that setbacks like this are an inherent part of racing. It's a tough pill to swallow, but it's a reality we face.

Yet, amidst the disappointment, there's an undeniable power in racing that sets my soul ablaze. In those challenging moments, I found solace in asking myself, "What would my 80-year-old self reflect about this day?" That's the person who truly matters to me. I can imagine her smiling and saying, "You gave it everything you had." And in that moment, she would fondly remember just how fully she lived her life.

Give these a try! - Including plyometrics in your training regimen as a triathlete and runner can provide numerous benefits. Plyometric exercises, which involve explosive movements like jumping and bounding, help improve power, speed, and agility. They enhance muscular strength, particularly in the lower body, leading to more efficient running and cycling stride. Plyometrics also promote better coordination and proprioception, which are crucial for navigating uneven terrains and quick transitions in triathlon. However, caution must be exercised when starting plyometrics. Begin with low-impact exercises and gradually progress to higher intensity movements to prevent injury. Allowing for adequate rest and recovery between sessions, ideally every few days, is essential for optimal adaptation and injury prevention. @angelanaethcoaching  @garminfitness

A 3/20 FTP test, or Functional Threshold Power test, assesses a cyclist's sustainable power output, representing the highest average power maintainable for an hour. During the test, cyclists aim for peak power in both 3 and 20-minute intervals, helping tailor training zones for personalized workouts based on fitness levels.

FTP tests require a proper warm-up, consistent pacing, and focus, providing valuable insights for optimizing training programs and improving cycling performance. Combining heart rate data with power metrics during the test offers a comprehensive assessment of cardiovascular and muscular responses.
